  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Global AgeWatch Index: Understanding the capabilities and empowerment of older people in the BRICS countries</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The aim of this project is to provide an in-depth understanding of the quality of life and well-being of older people living in four of the most populous countries in the world &#x2013; China (1st), India (2nd), Pakistan (6th) and Bangladesh (7th) &#x2013; and feed this evidence into national and international debates about ageing and human development.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To explore 5 research questions:
1. What is the conceptual pertinence of various dimensions (e.g. income security; health status; employment and other coping capacities; the enabling physical and social environments) in measuring quality of life and well-being of older people? 
2. How does the multidimensional measures of the quality of life and well-being of older people vary by five demographic and socio-economic attributes (age, gender, education, living arrangements and regions of residence (rural/urban, provinces)? To what extent the combination of these attributes may generate additive (exponential) disadvantage?
3. What are the policy contexts in which such differences across socio-economic groups prevail and what could be the role of social and economic policy in maintaining or accentuating these differences? How can policy making in one country provide important lessons for national policy formulation in other countries?   
4. What policy reforms are required in the focus countries to improve the situation of older men and older women, taking into account their demographic and socio- economic contexts?
5. What lessons can be drawn to support future editions of the Global Age Watch Index, in the choice of domains, in the selection of indicators, in the methodology of data aggregation and data comparison? What additional data is essential at the national/sub-national level, and in the international databases, to enrich analysis of quality of life and well-being of older people?</narrative>
  </description>
